Miles Morales

For his ID, he tried to get away with wearing his silkie in the picture (his dad ofc, told him to take it off)

He bought a Latino cook book for his mom and tried to make pupusas. The cheese was so thick though that he broke her favorite wooden spoon.

He tried to become a viner and often got his dad to play along with his skits. Sadly, vine died before Miles got the chance to really become famous.

Miles cried after reading Like Water for Chocolate (in Spanish and in English)

tags: Spider Man Into The Spider Verse
summary: Insomniac and Into The Spider-Verse, what we should have gotten for Peter Parker in the MCU
title: Insomniac and Into The Spider-Verse, what we should have gotten for Peter Parker in the MCU
body:
Insomniac’s Spider-Man and Into The Spider-Verse are both examples of what the MCU’s Spider-Man should have been. Both Insomniac and Into The Spider-Verse have shown that we want an older and more mature Peter. A Peter who struggles with adulthood, struggles with his job and family. A Spider-Man who has been active for years who is his own hero is something we’d all love and Peter mentoring Miles Morales is something we should’ve gotten in the MCU.

The problem I have with the MCU’s Peter Parker is that Marvel won’t let him grow up and be his own hero.  Peter Parker is a genius. He doesn’t need to be over reliant on Tony Stark. And for that matter, Peter doesn’t need to be in high school. Which brings me to my issue with how Marvel treats Peter Parker. They never let him grow up as a character. How many times do I need to see Peter Parker go to high school and graduate? I’ve seen Peter in High School more than I’ve seen Uncle Ben shot.  Peter is reliant on Tony Stark for his Spider suit,  I’m pretty sure they would’ve tried to make Tony the one who made his web shooters or even responsible for Peter’s powers, but they knew that would’ve pissed everyone off. I get annoyed every time Peter turns into Tony’s yes man “Mr Stark” this, “Mr Stark” that. I honestly would rather see Peter and Tony as peers. Peter is more interested in impressing Tony Stark than being his own hero. Spider-Man isn’t Robin, Spider-Man is his own hero. MCU’s Peter isn’t his own hero and Marvel just won’t let him grow up as a character. 

We are shown GREAT examples of Peter being older and more mature and allowed to be his own hero and a mentor to the younger generation. We don’t want kid Peter given everything by Tony. We want Peter to be his own hero, we want him to have agency and we want to see him mentor Miles. Insomniac and Into The Spider-Verse are what we should’ve gotten for Peter Parker in the MCU.
